[Wong] I don't know why
I like to eat these with my hands.

30:08.807 --> 30:11.601
I'm a real, like, handsy pervert
when it comes to dumplings. [laughs]

30:11.684 --> 30:13.603
I'm like, "Come over here
and let me feel you."

30:15.814 --> 30:18.483
[Chang] It's just delicious, too, right?

30:18.566 --> 30:21.528
So, this is never...
Even though it has a Michelin star,

30:21.611 --> 30:23.238
soup dumplings
and dumplings in general,

30:23.321 --> 30:26.241
it's never considered as artistic
and beautiful, as like a ravioli.

30:26.324 --> 30:27.784
Or delicate. Right.

30:27.867 --> 30:30.203
Here's another thing.
This price point, right?

30:30.286 --> 30:34.249
If I had this plate, and I put it
on a plate of ravioli...

30:34.332 --> 30:35.792
-Like, three of them.
-Three of them.

30:35.875 --> 30:37.126
For three times the price.

30:37.210 --> 30:38.878
Yeah, and it's with ricotta
and it's delicious.

30:38.962 --> 30:41.923
I'd eat it, you'd eat it,
but it'd be, like, 27, 28 bucks.

30:42.006 --> 30:42.841
Yeah.

30:42.924 --> 30:45.760
This is eight bucks. Or eight, nine bucks.

30:45.844 --> 30:47.512
Why is that?

30:49.347 --> 30:51.182
That's the shit that gets me mad.

30:51.266 --> 30:52.809
Well, it doesn't get me mad.

30:52.892 --> 30:56.688
It just makes me feel like
non-Asian people get bamboozled easier.

30:56.771 --> 30:57.605
[laughs]

30:57.689 --> 31:00.942
'Cause I hope they do not catch on,
and feel like they can... [chuckles]

31:02.193 --> 31:04.529
Don't tell them
what Italian people are doing.

31:04.612 --> 31:07.115
'Cause if they start charging more,
it would be, like, outrage.

31:07.198 --> 31:09.951
I think everybody knows
that what you're paying for is ambience,

31:10.034 --> 31:12.996
and some bullshit story about
where mushrooms came from from the waiter.

31:13.079 --> 31:13.955
[laughs] Right.

31:14.038 --> 31:16.457
And people eat that shit up.
I eat that shit up.

31:16.541 --> 31:19.711
But I don't think anybody
who really knows food,

31:19.794 --> 31:22.463
really thinks that that food is better.

31:28.511 --> 31:31.180
[Chang] I'm really struggling
with this idea.

31:31.264 --> 31:36.144
How does food become legitimate
because of its environment?

31:37.312 --> 31:41.399
Traditionally, fine dining
was white tablecloths, linens,

31:41.482 --> 31:43.902
flowers, people in penguin suits,

31:43.985 --> 31:47.530
and for many years,
that was where the best food lived.

31:52.869 --> 31:54.996
And it's something
I think I've historically

31:55.079 --> 31:57.373
always tried to push the buttons of,

31:57.457 --> 32:00.251
is stripping away the nonsense
and just getting to the food.

32:03.630 --> 32:09.093
A dumpling, whether it's Italian or Asian,
is something that is humble in origin.

32:12.180 --> 32:17.518
It's about stretching ingredients,
using scraps, being as frugal as possible.

32:23.316 --> 32:25.944
Do you make
the best dumplings in the area?

32:26.027 --> 32:28.613
[in Mandarin] Well, I wouldn't say that!
[chuckling]

32:28.696 --> 32:30.031
Just average.

32:31.449 --> 32:34.744
We northerners love eating dumplings.
[chuckles]

32:36.704 --> 32:38.957
For dumplings, chop the leaves,
not the root.

32:39.999 --> 32:41.584
Chopping the root
makes the water come out.

32:42.251 --> 32:44.629
[Chang in English] Do all the vegetables
come from her garden?

32:44.712 --> 32:45.964
[Wei in Mandarin] I planted them myself.

32:46.047 --> 32:48.633
The dough for dumplings
requires cool water.

32:49.801 --> 32:50.843
[Chang in English]
Do you have running water?

32:51.552 --> 32:52.428
[Wei chuckles]

32:53.012 --> 32:54.555
[in Mandarin] There's no water now.

32:54.639 --> 32:55.807
[translator]
Because it's cold? It's frozen?

32:55.890 --> 32:56.849
No, not that.

32:56.933 --> 32:59.769
We have half-day water here.

32:59.852 --> 33:02.230
Yeah. We don't have any now.
After 9:00 a.m., there's no more.

33:02.313 --> 33:03.356
[Chang in English] Wow.

33:05.358 --> 33:06.859
[Wei in Mandarin] And now the filling.

33:08.069 --> 33:11.447
Spring onions, ginger, garlic.
Then add salt.

33:11.531 --> 33:13.366
Monosodium glutamate.

33:13.449 --> 33:14.742
[Chang in English] MSG?

33:15.535 --> 33:16.661
[in Mandarin] Dark soy sauce.

33:18.579 --> 33:20.164
This is sunflower oil.

33:21.457 --> 33:23.376
This'll do.

33:23.459 --> 33:27.922
[Chang] The fact that they don't have gas,
no running water...

33:28.006 --> 33:32.844
When I just sort of fathom how hard it is
for them to make everything,

33:32.927 --> 33:35.096
that's when I was like,
"Oh, it's a privilege to be here."

33:46.315 --> 33:47.859
It feels like growing up at home.

33:47.942 --> 33:50.194
The women in my family
used to just make dumplings.

33:50.278 --> 33:52.697
They would just make
hundreds and hundreds.

33:52.780 --> 33:55.992
This isn't so different than, like,
an Italian grandma

33:56.075 --> 33:59.912
making, you know,
a ravioli or something like that.

34:02.749 --> 34:04.333
[Wei in Mandarin] Try wrapping them.

34:06.753 --> 34:09.255
[in English] It's like they're
putting pressure in...

34:12.257 --> 34:14.802
They make it look so easy.
It's not easy at all.

34:14.886 --> 34:20.933
Look how beautiful theirs are
and how stone-hands-like mine are.

34:21.016 --> 34:23.770
How long would it take for me
to get good at this?

34:23.853 --> 34:25.730
[in Mandarin] It wouldn't take long.

34:25.813 --> 34:29.358
[woman] Pretty quick. Two months.

34:29.442 --> 34:34.155
[Wei] You're like our kid. We wrap
dumplings and you want to help out.

34:38.409 --> 34:42.914
Stuff some of the firewood in
and the water will boil.

34:47.835 --> 34:50.505
[Chang in English] I just think
that when you make food this way,

34:50.588 --> 34:52.422
it's gotta taste better.

34:52.507 --> 34:55.760
'Cause you worked so goddamn hard.
It's like, "How much do you care?"

34:56.928 --> 34:59.972
When you realize, from start to finish,
you've been busting your ass, you know,

35:00.056 --> 35:04.852
why would you go so far into this process
only to make it taste halfway?

35:04.936 --> 35:08.189
[in Mandarin] Hu, I'll give you this tray.
Give me that tray.

35:10.149 --> 35:11.567
[sighs]

35:11.651 --> 35:14.445
[in English] She doesn't wanna cook mine.
[chuckles]

35:16.697 --> 35:19.784
[in Mandarin] Those would burst
if they were boiled. [laughs]

35:22.120 --> 35:24.038
[Chang in English] That looks so cool.

35:24.956 --> 35:26.374
Looks so cool.

35:31.254 --> 35:32.588
[indistinct chatter]

35:36.008 --> 35:40.513
[in Italian] So, like that. Okay, not bad.
You only put little filling, little pesto.

35:40.596 --> 35:42.765
How beautiful! How beautiful!

35:44.267 --> 35:45.601
How is it going?

35:45.685 --> 35:47.895
Very well.

35:47.979 --> 35:50.690
Well, very well.

35:51.482 --> 35:53.025
Very well.

35:53.776 --> 35:56.696
-Buongiorno.
-Buongiorno, David.

35:56.779 --> 35:58.573
[Chang in English] It's almost
every Saturday they're trying to do this?

35:58.656 --> 36:00.491
-[Bottura] Two times a week.
-Two times a week.

36:00.575 --> 36:05.246
And the grandmothers, they transfer
the knowledge to the kids as--

36:05.329 --> 36:06.539
[Chang] So it's the nonnas' ideas.

36:06.622 --> 36:11.878
Yes. Point was, what they're gonna do,
these kids?

36:11.961 --> 36:15.256
Once, uh, the school is over, high school.
You know?

36:15.339 --> 36:17.967
So, they start like this, you know?

36:18.050 --> 36:23.222
To produce something with their finger,
work with a little movement.

36:23.306 --> 36:25.641
But the idea is the grandmother,

36:25.725 --> 36:30.646
they have, uh, all this knowledge
since their grandmothers...

36:30.730 --> 36:35.109
Why don't we transfer that knowledge
to these kids?

36:35.193 --> 36:41.782
They're gonna be like the witness,
the people carrying the knowledge.

36:44.327 --> 36:47.455
[Chang] I just feel like this whole...

36:47.538 --> 36:50.666
The history of it, passing down
from generation to generation,

36:50.750 --> 36:53.753
-this is, like, a transcultural thing.
-Yeah.

36:53.836 --> 36:56.881
I did this with my mother and grandmother.

36:56.964 --> 37:00.301
[Bottura] I couldn't be the one I am

37:00.384 --> 37:06.390
if my grandmother didn't transfer
this kind of, uh, emotional experience

37:06.474 --> 37:07.892
when I was a kid.

37:09.769 --> 37:11.270
But look at that.

37:11.354 --> 37:16.234
What is the meaning of the tortellino?
That each one of them is totally different

37:16.317 --> 37:20.655
because it is reflecting the personality
of each one of us.

37:36.295 --> 37:37.797
[Taka Kondo] Hmm. Mmm-hmm.

37:38.756 --> 37:40.049
That's real good.

37:42.551 --> 37:44.178
[Chang] Fuck. Food here is so good.

37:44.262 --> 37:45.263
[Kondo] Yeah.

37:45.346 --> 37:46.597
This market, I like it.

37:47.807 --> 37:49.850
You've been in Modena ten years.

37:49.934 --> 37:51.143
Yeah, more like 13 years.

37:51.227 --> 37:54.814
Thirteen years. And you moved from Tokyo
straight to here?

37:54.897 --> 37:58.442
[Kondo] Yeah. I always worked
at an Italian restaurant in Japan.

37:58.526 --> 38:02.655
-Right.
-I wanted to see Italian culture in Italy.

38:03.531 --> 38:05.574
You know, Japanese are, like,
more focused.

38:05.658 --> 38:08.160
Italian people more creative.

38:12.164 --> 38:15.042
Taka's gonna make the Osteria version
of the tortellini.

38:17.253 --> 38:21.799
But do you think the Modena tortellini
has reached the evolutionary peak?

38:21.882 --> 38:23.175
Is that... Can't be better.

38:23.259 --> 38:27.680
[Bottura] In the last ten years,
we developed the perfect filling,

38:27.763 --> 38:29.890
with the perfect parmigiano,
the perfect prosciutto,

38:29.974 --> 38:34.186
the perfect mortadella.
Yes, I think we reached the peak.

38:41.360 --> 38:44.780
[chuckling] It's delicious.
What a surprise.

38:48.617 --> 38:50.995
I think we're gonna try to make, uh,
in theory,

38:51.078 --> 38:54.123
tiny, tiny wontons,
essentially, in a tortellini.

38:54.206 --> 38:57.585
Because tortellini en brodo
is the same thing as wonton soup, so...

38:57.668 --> 39:01.964
I was trying to make, like,
dumplings in the form of tortellini.

39:02.048 --> 39:04.133
We have some pork
and we have some veal in here.

39:04.216 --> 39:09.847
I'm not sure about any of this stuff.
I feel like I'm in enemy territory here.

39:09.930 --> 39:13.517
But number one, I discovered,
you actually need egg,

39:13.601 --> 39:16.979
or some kind of different flour
to make it a little bit more sturdy.

39:19.190 --> 39:21.025
Such a wet dough.

39:21.108 --> 39:25.488
Everything was going swimmingly well and
I needed some flour to roll out my dough,

39:25.571 --> 39:28.616
and then, all of a sudden,
a bucket appeared,

39:28.699 --> 39:33.162
and I start folding some in,
I put some on the board...

39:33.245 --> 39:37.666
[chuckles] And then all of a sudden
I'm like, "What the fuck's going on?"

39:37.750 --> 39:38.793
[laughs] What happened?

39:38.876 --> 39:42.380
My dough starts to just, like,
melt, almost. It's so sticky.

39:42.463 --> 39:43.839
And then Taka's like...

39:44.507 --> 39:45.674
This is rice flour?

39:45.758 --> 39:48.761
Is this flour? It's not flour.

39:48.844 --> 39:49.762
This is--

39:49.845 --> 39:52.014
-This is maltodextrin.
-[laughs]

39:53.140 --> 39:57.436
-Tapioca maltodextrin! I put it all on--
-Oh, my God. Oh, my God. No.

39:57.520 --> 40:00.481
-Taka sabotaged me.
-[Kondo chuckles]

40:00.564 --> 40:03.317
-But he's on your side, Taka, come on!
-[laughing]

40:03.984 --> 40:05.361
[Chang] Oh, I'm so stupid.

40:05.444 --> 40:08.197
I can't believe I put maltodextrin
on my goddamn flour.

40:09.198 --> 40:10.074
[laughing]

40:10.157 --> 40:13.285
Worst thing in the world you could add.

40:19.125 --> 40:23.254
-Sorry, guys. The dough is terrible.
-Yeah.

40:23.337 --> 40:25.172
[laughing]

40:25.923 --> 40:27.174
[coughs]

40:27.925 --> 40:29.093
[Chang] Oh.

40:29.969 --> 40:31.262
I've been humbled.

40:31.345 --> 40:35.182
Because I was never understanding
of the quality of the ingredients

40:35.266 --> 40:37.935
that goes into it, which is ultimately
what makes Italian food Italian food.

40:38.018 --> 40:38.978
Yeah.

40:39.061 --> 40:41.230
Whenever I'm making dumplings
or eating dumplings,

40:41.313 --> 40:43.274
I'm never thinking about
the quality of the ingredients.

40:43.357 --> 40:44.191
Absolutely.

40:45.276 --> 40:46.902
[Chang]
Can I eat a delicious dumpling? Yes.

40:46.986 --> 40:50.948
Is there a lot of craftsmanship that goes
into a soup dumpling? 100%.

40:51.031 --> 40:52.032
That's awesome.

40:52.825 --> 40:55.786
But I can't tell you
about the provenance of the meat,

40:55.870 --> 40:58.164
or the kind of crab or anything.

40:58.247 --> 41:00.291
Oh, I didn't see it
from your guys' perspective.

41:01.792 --> 41:05.504
I can't make dumplings
the same vein of a tortellini.

41:05.588 --> 41:07.798
I just can't merge cultures, right?

41:07.882 --> 41:10.050
That's not my story to tell.

41:10.134 --> 41:13.387
Maybe Taka's kids, 50 years from now,

41:13.471 --> 41:16.599
will be like, "I've an idea for gyoza."
And that happens.

41:16.682 --> 41:18.350
[Bottura] Absolutely!

41:18.434 --> 41:23.481
The tradition are changing because
it's the moving, all these migrants.

41:24.315 --> 41:31.071
And maybe there are new sparkle
of new flavors that are coming up.

41:32.490 --> 41:36.827
[Bowerman] There are some ingredients
in some dishes that would not even exist

41:36.911 --> 41:41.749
if that cross-pollination didn't exist
at one point in history.

41:41.832 --> 41:44.752
[Carbone] This is borderline Asian.
It's all umami.

41:45.586 --> 41:47.421
[Chang] I will say
where there's similarities,

41:47.505 --> 41:49.798
whether it be Italian
or Chinese dumplings,

41:49.882 --> 41:53.636
was the image of a grandma making it.

41:53.719 --> 41:55.846
I don't know, that's just love, right?

41:55.930 --> 41:58.891
Do you ever get tired of eating dumplings
and making dumplings?

41:59.642 --> 42:01.560
[in Mandarin] I wouldn't. [laughs]

42:02.269 --> 42:03.479
Eat up.

42:04.605 --> 42:07.024
[Bottura in English] And when you bite,
then you say...

42:07.107 --> 42:10.444
"Wow, what is this?
I never taste something like this."

42:10.528 --> 42:14.073
This is the very important point
for people like us.

42:14.156 --> 42:19.453
Because we are in search of perfection
and emotions in food.

42:19.537 --> 42:21.664
Because at the end, it's all about that.

42:25.334 --> 42:28.754
[Chang] I appreciate, again, my friend

42:28.837 --> 42:31.423
for coming
and talking about his people's food.

42:31.507 --> 42:35.844
And obviously, Italian food's the most
popular food in the world right now.

42:35.928 --> 42:39.348
I'd like to begin my closing statement

42:39.431 --> 42:43.269
by admitting how much
I absolutely love this man and his food.

42:43.352 --> 42:45.479
-[audience] Aw...
-I admire what you do

42:45.563 --> 42:47.189
-and I do love Asian noodles.
-[Chang] Mmm.

42:47.273 --> 42:48.357
Generally when I'm wasted.

42:48.440 --> 42:49.400
[laughing]

42:49.483 --> 42:51.777
And with that, we'll conclude
our debate tonight.

42:51.860 --> 42:53.404
There's no resolution to this.

42:53.487 --> 42:55.531
[audience applauding and cheering]

42:55.614 --> 42:57.908
I'm wearing a winter coat as a blazer.

42:58.492 --> 43:00.661
[audience applauding and cheering]

43:03.330 --> 43:04.498
[Chang] Hmm.

